# Tier 3 — The hexboard care playground (handoff)

**Audience:** the story/content + asset dev. **Goal of Tier 3:** the hexboard becomes a living
"second way to care" — the gotchi wanders on its own, and you stock the board with items it seeks
out and consumes for stat gains. This is the **hex** half of the theme. It's **optional**: the base
game (Tiers 0–1) ships without it, so nothing here blocks the endgame.

Tags: **[ENGINE]** engine/behavior, **[DESIGN]** the item/stat mapping, **[ASSET]** pixel art.

**Where we are:** slot 3 is delivering the core loop — 3 placeholder objects that drop onto hexes
and get consumed when the gotchi stands on them. The rest is: autonomy, expanding 3 → 8 items with
correct stat effects, and the art.

---

## Item A — Gotchi autonomous decision-making  **[ENGINE]**

Right now the gotchi only moves when you drop an item (or click a hex). Give it simple autonomy so
the board feels alive. This is a tiny behavior layer on top of slot 3's existing seek — **not**
complex AI, and per `GAME_DESIGN.mx §4b` it stays a **straight-line seek** (`setTargetPosition` /
`moveToTarget` / `wander`), no pathfinding unless the board has impassable tiles.

Goal selection each time the gotchi goes idle, in priority order:
1. **Nearest un-consumed item on the board** → seek it. (This is what makes "drop food, watch him
   go eat it" work without you setting the target manually — the drop just places the item; the
   gotchi *decides* to go get it.)
2. **Otherwise wander** — pick a random reachable hex, optionally biased toward liked biomes and
   away from disliked ones (tiles already carry a "he likes it / doesn't" flavor per §4b). Keep it
   loose and idle-looking.

Reconcile with what exists: a **manual hex-click** (slot 3's move) is a high-priority temporary
goal that overrides the AI; when it arrives / goes idle, autonomy resumes. Consume-on-arrival
(slot 3's mechanic) stays exactly as is — the AI just chooses the targets now.

---

## Item B — The 8-item set  **[DESIGN + ENGINE]**

Extend slot 3's 3-placeholder mechanic to 8 items. Each item, when the gotchi reaches it, applies
its stat effects and is consumed. Use the **real stat path** the buttons use (`addStat` /
`feed()` / etc. per `GOTCHI_ACTION_STAT_GAINS.md`) — don't duplicate stat math.

**The one hard rule:** only the **Ball** feeds a hidden driver (affection, via a warmth
`CareAction`), matching the Tier 1 fix (affection = pet/play/ball only). Every other item affects
**visible/reserved stats only — no hidden driver.** Food/rest/etc. must not touch affection or
mercy, or you re-introduce the spreadsheet-caretaker bug on the hex side.

These 8 also deliberately fill the categories the button system reserved for the hexboard (Social,
Skill, Physical — see the doc's "Future-Reserved Actions"), so the board exercises stats the
buttons never touch.

| # | Item | Fills / affects (real stat names) | Hidden driver? |
|---|------|-----------------------------------|----------------|
| 1 | **Ball** (play) | `EXCITEMENT` ++, `HAPPINESS` +, `LOVE` +, `AGILITY` + (Physical) | **Yes — warmth `CareAction` → affection** |
| 2 | **Food bowl** | `FOOD_LEVEL` −− (fills hunger; 0=full), `SATISFACTION` + | no |
| 3 | **Water bowl** | `HYDRATION` −− (fills thirst; 0=hydrated), `SATISFACTION` + | no |
| 4 | **Soap / bath** | `CLEANLINESS` ++ (hygiene), `SATISFACTION` + | no |
| 5 | **Bed / cushion** | `ENERGY` +, `SLEEP_DEBT` − (rest; 0=rested), `HAPPINESS` + | no |
| 6 | **Puzzle / block toy** | `LEARNING` +, `MEMORY` + (Skill), `EXCITEMENT` + | no |
| 7 | **Buddy / plush** | `FRIENDS` +, `POPULARITY` +, `FRIEDNSHIP` + (Social) | no |
| 8 | **Medicine / berry** | `FITALITY` + (Health) | no |

Notes for whoever wires the effects:
- Watch the **inverted vitals**: `FOOD_LEVEL` / `HYDRATION` / `SLEEP_DEBT` are 0=good, 100=bad, so
  "filling" them means **subtracting**. `CLEANLINESS` / `ENERGY` / `FITALITY` are normal (+).
- `FRIEDNSHIP` is the **intentional misspelling** in the enum — use it exactly (per the doc).
- Magnitudes are tunable; start comparable to the matching button (e.g. Food ≈ the −30 the Feed
  button gives), then tune.

Coverage check: this spread hits play/affection, hunger, thirst, hygiene, rest, skill, social, and
health — a full care surface without overlapping the ending drivers beyond the Ball.

---

## Item C — 32×32 pixel art  **[ASSET]**

Eight 32×32 icons, one per item above, in the game's retro palette. Requirements: readable as a
silhouette at 32px, transparent background, consistent limited palette across the set, and legible
both in the hotbar slot and dropped on a hex tile. Slot 3's colored-shape placeholders keep working
until these land, so this doesn't block A or B — it's a straight swap of the placeholder draw for
the loaded texture. (Pick items whose 32px silhouettes are distinct — a ball, a bowl, a bed, etc.
read instantly; avoid two round bowls that look identical.)

---

## Sequencing & definition of done

1. **Item A (autonomy)** [ENGINE] — layer goal-selection on slot 3's seek; drops become goals,
   idle → wander.
2. **Item B (8 items)** [DESIGN + ENGINE] — expand the hotbar + item table to 8, wire each to its
   real stats through the existing stat path, Ball-only affection.
3. **Item C (art)** [ASSET] — 8 × 32×32 icons; engine swaps placeholders for textures.

**Done =** you drop any of the 8 items on the board, the gotchi decides on its own to walk over and
consume it, the right stats move (and only the Ball nudges affection), and when the board's empty
the gotchi wanders on its own. Placeholders are fine for a working build; the pixel art is the
finishing pass.

---

## Guardrails (so it stays shallow and consistent)

- Straight-line seek, no pathfinding, per §4b — unless the board actually has impassable tiles.
- **Only the Ball feeds a hidden driver.** This is the same discipline as the button fix — the
  moment food or a bed nudges affection/mercy, hex-board caretaking corrupts the ending routing.
- Consume applies effects through the **existing** stat path, not a parallel copy.
- This whole tier is bonus. If time gets tight, the game is complete without it — don't let art
  polish or the 8th item hold up anything in Tiers 0–2.
